text.__SUMMARY__:
Acacia julifera is a tree belonging to the genus Acacia and the subgenus Juliflorae that is native to north eastern Australia.
The tree typically grows to a maximum height of 7.5 m (25 ft) or as a shrub with a straggly habit to a height of around 3.5 m (11 ft). It has reddish, greyish brown or black coloured bark that is tough and fibrous. The slender and slightly flattened branchlets are a reddish or purplish brown colour and becone glabrous with age. Like most species of Acacia it has phyllodes rather than true leaves. It blooms between March and August producing golden flowers.It is endemic to south eastern parts of the Gulf of Carpentaria where it is found in coastal and sub-coastal districts .
